\maketitle

Topological phases of matter are presently one of the main research topics in condensed matter physics.
At the non-interacting level topological phases of non-interacting fermions are systematically classified in a general spatial dimension and symmetry class \cite{kitaev22,schnyderPRB08,schnyderAIP}. Similar to quantum Hall states, topological insulators (TIs) \cite{Konig2012,Hsieh2008}  and superconductors (TSCs) are gapped systems hosting gapless modes on their surfaces, insensitive to small perturbations \cite{Hasan2010a,qiZhangRMP11}. The robustness of these surface states relies on the existence of discrete antiunitary symmetries, either time-reversal (TRS), ${\mathcal{T}}$, and (or) particle-hole symmetry, ${C}$. Thus, such phases are denoted symmetry protected topological phases (SPT).
A natural question is whether the classification changes in the presence of electron-electron interactions that do not break explicitly or spontaneously the protecting symmetries. Fidkowski and Kitaev \cite{Fidkowski2010} showed that an interaction could adiabatically connect two states that are topologically distinct in its absence. This example involved one dimensional (1D) spinless p-wave superconductors with TRS (class BDI), where it was shown that an interaction involving eight Majorana operators reduces the topological classification from ${\mathds{Z}}$ to ${\mathds{Z}}_8$. Two gapped quadratic Hamiltonian whose topological invariants differ by eight can be connected by a gap-preserving trajectory involving the interaction.
Consequently, if two semi-infinite wires at these two phases are connected by an interface, the eight Majorana zero modes that are localized at the interface are gapped by the interaction.
Subsequently, the full topological classification of interacting 1D SPT phases was obtained \cite{Turner2011,Fidkowski2011a,Tang2012}, as well as some examples in two \cite{Yao2013a,Qi2013a,Gu2014} and three dimensions \cite{Wang2014c,Senthil2014a,Vishwanath2013}. An exhaustive classification of short-range entangled SPTs phases still remains subject of intense research, where methods such as cobordism \cite{Kapustin2014}, group (super)-cohomology \cite{Gu2012} and non-linear sigma model \cite{Morimoto2015a} are used.

In this work we address the question of
``What is the topological classification of interacting fermionic topological systems in a given spatial dimension $d$ and symmetry $s$, when the classification in the absence of interactions is ${\mathds{Z}}$?".
We derive and employ a correspondence between the topological invariant $\nu$ of the $d$-dimensional bulk and the number
$n_{\rm 0D}$ of zero-energy bound states localized at zero-dimensional (0D) topological defects
on its $(d-1)$ surface. 
We argue that when the zero modes localized in \emph{any} 0D topological defect are gapped by an interaction,
the state becomes topologically trivial under the same interaction. The argument is made explicit by piercing the surface with a lattice of defects. Our analysis reproduces the classification obtained in \cite{Morimoto2015a}, adding a simple physical picture and an explicit form of the interaction that gaps the surface.

There is an important distinction between classes with ${\mathds{Z}}$ topology in even and odd dimensions. Even-dimensional ${\mathds{Z}}$ classes
host {\it chiral} modes on the boundaries whose gapping is forbidden by the conservation of energy. Odd dimensional ${\mathds{Z}}$ classes host nonchiral (helical) boundary modes whose protection depends on the presence of chiral symmetry.  Following Refs.~\cite{Qi2013a,Yao2013a}, we find it  useful to construct nonchiral SPT phases in even dimensions
by combining two systems with opposite chirality and Chern invariant, and adding another ${\mathds{Z}}_2$ unitary symmetry ${R}$ that prevents the coupling of edge modes of opposite chirality.
The resulting classes, which we refer as prime ($'$) classes, represent a natural generalization of SPT phases to even dimensions, and including them makes our analysis  equally applicable to even and odd dimensions.

We pursue an analogous path to Ref.~\cite{Teo2010}, in
its description of the ten-fold classification of non-interacting topological states 
using a eight- or two-hour ``Bott clock". We relate the topological character of a SPT class with symmetry $s$ in dimension $d$ 
to one with $s+1$ and $d+1$ (Fig.~\ref{clock}), and find that in
  the presence of interactions, ${\mathds{Z}}$ is reduced to ${\mathds{Z}}_n$, 
with $n$ violating the clock periodicity.  This is represented as a spiral clock in Figs.\ref{clock}(a)-(c),
distinguished by their $d=1$ symmetry classes:
 (a) BDI (b) CII and (c) AIII. Generally,

