Analogously, we can describe a chain in class BDI by Eq.~\eqref{aiiiham}, where the fermionic operators $c$ are replaced by Majorana operators $\eta$, for which $\eta_{L,R}^{\dagger}= \eta_{L,R}$ holds. In this basis, charge conjugation $C$ is the identity, and ${\mathcal{T}}={\mathcal{S}}$.
The edge Majorana bound states are formed by $\gamma = \int \! {\rm d} x (\eta_L + \eta_R) {\text{sech}~} x$, localized at $x=0$. Pairing the operators $\gamma_i$  into  complex fermions $\psi_i = \gamma_{2i-1} + i \gamma_{2i}$, we achieve the same symmetry relations as in class AIII. 
Hence, Eq.~\eqref{aiiiint} satisfies the symmetries of class BDI and can be used to gap out groups of 8 Majoranas, resulting in the reduction ${\mathds{Z}} \rightarrow {\mathds{Z}}_8$ ($n=8$).
Using similar considerations, we 
conclude that $n=2$ in class CII, where the Hamiltonian acts on spinful fermions with an intrinsic double degeneracy.

\emph{From one to two dimensions --}
In two dimensions we focus on class D$'$, Fig.~\ref{fig1}(a).
The analysis for A$'$ and C$'$ proceeds similarly.
In all cases we find $n_{\rm 0D}=\nu$, such that the step  from $d=1$ to $d=2$ does not increase $n$.
Class D$'$ can be constructed by adding two copies of 2D $p$-wave superconductors with broken TRS (class D), bearing electrons of opposite spin direction and gapless edge modes of opposite chirality. The resulting system has TRS  with ${\mathcal{T}}^2=-1$,
but an additional ${\mathds{Z}}_2$ unitary symmetry, $R$, distinguishes it from the class DIII, in which an even number of pairs of counter-propagating edge modes may be gapped without violating TRS~\cite{note}. The symmetry $R$ can be physically implemented either as a conservation of $S_z$ modulo $2$ (i.e. conservation of the parity $(-1)^{N_{{\uparrow}}}$) which satisfies ${R}^2 = 1$ and $\{{\mathcal{T}},{R}\}=0$ \cite{Qi2013a,Yao2013a} or as a mirror symmetry satisfying ${R}^2 = -1$ and $[{\mathcal{T}},{R}]=0$ \cite{Yao2013a} in which case D$'$ corresponds to the crystalline phase DIII+R. In both options, the combined operator $\tilde{{\mathcal{T}}} = {\mathcal{T}} {R}$ is antiunitary and satisfies $\tilde{{\mathcal{T}}}^2 = 1$. Here, we choose the first ${R}$ realization.
The D$'$ system has zero Chern number $N_{{\uparrow}} + N_{{\downarrow}} = 0$ but a non-zero spin Chern number $\frac{1}{2}(N_{{\uparrow}} - N_{{\downarrow}}) $, resulting in a ${\mathds{Z}}$ topological classification at the non-interacting level.

