Locally, ${\mathcal{H}}_m$ breaks both ${\mathcal{T}}$ and ${R}$ but preserves the combination $\tilde{{\mathcal{T}}} = {\mathcal{T}} {R}$. Consequently, the resulting edge Hamiltonian ${\mathcal{H}}_{\rm D'}+{\mathcal{H}}_m$ has the antiunitary symmetry $\tilde{{\mathcal{T}}}$ squaring to $+1$, representing spinless fermions (class BDI). { As in the previous section, we choose the mass $m(x)$ to change sign at $x=0$  to form a 0D mass defect and find $\nu$ Majorana bound states
at $x=0$.
Thus, in the noninteracting limit the 1D BDI system constructed at the boundary inherits the topology of the bulk 2D system of class D$'$. 
If the mass oscillates in space $m(x)=m_0\cos(qx)$ a lattice of 0D defects is formed with a separation of $2\pi/q$. When each defect contains eight zero modes, the interaction between the zero modes may be used to induce the topological transition from $m_0>0$ to $m_0<0$ without 
closing the energy gap~\cite{Qi2013a} leading to $n=8$.

